## Confession good for the body

If it is truly not feasible for you to connect to more people, there is one more cheap route to improving health and well-being. It is variously called "expressive writing", "confessional writing", and "emotional journaling", and you can do it alone. A number of studies have been done on the health effects of jounaling. The doyen of such researchers is Dr. James Pennebaker, who writes that[^^c03n06]

{blockquote}
...writing or talking about emotional experiences, relative to writing about superficial control topics, has been found to be associated with significant drops in physician visits... to have beneficial influences on immune function... Students who write about emotional topics show improvements in grades in the months following... professionals who have been laid off from their jobs get jobs more quickly after writing... staff members who write about emotional topics are subsequently absent from their work at lower rates than control participants.
{/blockquote}

These results are based in controlled experiments. A typical experiment[^^c03n06a] tested the effect on patients suffering from asthma and arthritis. Some patients for several days wrote down, anonymously, their "deepest thoughts" about the most stressful event in their lives, typically a death, or a childhood incident. The control group spent the same amount of time writing down plans for that day.

The patients who wrote about stressful things displayed improvements in their disease symptoms that lasted for months. Half the experimental group improved over four months, against 25% of the controls; 20% of the controls got worse against only 5% of the experimental group.

What could be going on here? It can't be that the physical act of writing made a change in arthritic joints or asthmatic lungs! The results must have come from the *mental* act of organizing and then verbalizing thoughts about serious life events. That was the only difference between the two groups.

We know that this same mental act -- honestly recalling stressful events, and shaping those memories into words -- goes on in two other contexts:

* When intimate friends talk.
* When a believer prays.

We'll talk about the matter of prayer in [Chapter 4](#Chapter04). For now, it seems clear that confiding stories about the worst things that happen to you -- whether you tell them to a trusted friend or to a keyboard or a piece of paper -- can have a significant effect on your health.

## Summary

Social connectivity is not just a nice idea, it's a way of staying healthier and living longer. And it is reciprocal: other people need it as much as you, so by connecting with them, you are bestowing health and longer life on others. I've suggested looking for more and better social ties among:

* Secular Sunday congregations
* Your intimate family
* Your extended family and its history
* Your friends
* Your neighbors
* Your avocations and the affinity groups they lead you to
* Your work
* Volunteer services
* Online communities

Yes, you can find endless reasons for not making this effort: you don't really enjoy socializing or you actively fear it; the cost of time and money; the chance of having your autonomy reduced. But these reasons all evaporate or become small if you can accept that the end result is an improved, longer life for both you and the people you touch.
